Day 6: Network Analysis and Migration Flows

Adam Slez

Getting Started

Today we will learn how to the tidygraph and ggraph packages to manipulate, analyze, and visualize data on international migration flows. To do this, we will need to load the following libraries: tidyverse, igraph, tidygraph, ggraph, and DT.

library(tidyverse)
library(igraph)
library(tidygraph)
library(ggraph)
library(DT)

Load Data

Use the read_csv command to load the migration_2000.csv and totpop_2000.csv files.

mig_df <- read_csv("migration_2000.csv")
## Rows: 576 Columns: 5
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (4): origin_code, destination_code, origin_name, destination_name
## dbl (1): mig_count_2000
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
pop_df <- read.csv("totpop_2000.csv")

Drop Zero-Population Flows

If you look at the data, you will see that some country pairs have a value of zero for the number of people moving from the origin to the destination. Before turning the data into a network/graph, you will want to drop rows that have a value of zero on the mig_count_2000 variable. After dropping these rows, how many origins and destinations do you have?

mig_df <- mig_df %>%
  filter(mig_count_2000 > 0)
length(unique(mig_df$origin_name))
## [1] 24
length(unique(mig_df$destination_name))
## [1] 24

Convert Flows to a Graph

While we can do a ton of work with the current data, we can do even more if we convert it to a tbl_graph object. Toward this end, use the as_tbl_graph command to convert mig_df to a graph and merge the population data with the resulting node data.

mig_g <- as_tbl_graph(mig_df) 
mig_g <- mig_g %>%
  left_join(pop_df, by = c("name" = "country_code"))

Graph Properties

Use the count_components, diameter, and edge_density commands to calculate the following measures:

  • Number of weakly connected components
  • Weighted diameter
  • Density
count_components(mig_g, mode = "weak")
## [1] 1
diameter(mig_g, weights = E(mig_g)$mig_count_2000)
## [1] 3605
edge_density(mig_g)
## [1] 0.8804348

Unweighted Degree Centrality

Use the centrality_degree command to identify the top five countries associated with each of the following:

  • Total number of partners
  • Number of sending partners
  • Number of receiving partners
mig_g <- mig_g %>%
  mutate(deg_uw_tot = centrality_degree(mode = "total"),
         deg_uw_in = centrality_degree(mode = "in"),
         deg_uw_out = centrality_degree(mode = "out"))
mig_uw_df <- as.data.frame(mig_g) %>%
  select(country_name, country_code = name, contains("deg_uw"))
datatable(mig_uw_df)

Weighted Degree Centrality

Use the centrality_degree command to identify the top five countries associated with each of the following:

  • Total number of migrants
  • Number of incoming migrants
  • Number of outgoing migrants
mig_g <- mig_g %>%
  mutate(deg_wgt_tot = centrality_degree(mode = "total", 
                                         weight = mig_count_2000),
         deg_wgt_in = centrality_degree(mode = "in", 
                                        weight = mig_count_2000),
         deg_wgt_out = centrality_degree(mode = "out", 
                                         weight = mig_count_2000))
mig_wgt_df <- as.data.frame(mig_g) %>%
  select(country_name, country_code = name, contains("deg_wgt"))
datatable(mig_wgt_df)

Standardizing Flows

Migration flows are often modeled using what is known as the gravity model, which takes its name from the equation for the amount of gravitational force between physical bodies. In the traditional gravity equation the force of attraction between any given pair of bodies is positively associated with the product of their masses. When applying this model to migration flows, we use population in place of mass, highlighting the idea that places with more people are likely to send and receive more people because they are bigger. With this in mind, it makes sense to redo our analysis of the weighted flow data using standardized flows, keeping in mind that flows can be standardized in terms of the population of either the origin or the destination.

To do this, we’ll need to (a) switch to the edge side of the data using the activate function, and then (b) attach the information on population, which lives on the node side of the data, to the edge data using the context accessor .N().

mig_g <- mig_g %>%
  activate(edges) %>%
  mutate(origin_pop = .N()$totpop[from],
         destination_pop = .N()$totpop[to],
         mig_std_o = mig_count_2000 / origin_pop,
         mig_std_d = mig_count_2000 / destination_pop)

Weighted Degree Centrality Revisited

Use the centrality_degree command to identify the top five countries associated with each of the following:

  • Number of incoming migrants standardized by the population of the destination country
  • Number of outgoing migrants standardized by the population of the origin country
mig_g <- mig_g %>%
  activate(nodes) %>%
  mutate(deg_wgt_stdin = centrality_degree(mode = "in", 
                                           weight = mig_std_d),
         deg_wgt_stdout = centrality_degree(mode = "out", 
                                            weight = mig_std_o))
mig_stdwgt_df <- as.data.frame(mig_g) %>%
  select(country_name, country_code = name, totpop, contains("deg_wgt"))
datatable(mig_stdwgt_df)

Plot Standardized Flows

Use the ggraph command to plot destination-standardized flows.

ggraph(mig_g, weights = mig_std_d, layout = "fr") +
  geom_edge_fan(color = "grey65", alpha = 0.15,
                arrow = arrow(length = unit(2.5, "mm"),
                               type = "closed"),
                 end_cap = circle(1.5, "mm")) +
  geom_node_point(colour = "red") +
  geom_node_text(aes(label = name), repel = TRUE) +
  theme_graph()

Measure Coreness Using Eigenvector Centrality

Use the centrality_eigen command to measure the coreness of each node based on both raw and destination-standardized flows.

mig_g <- mig_g %>%
  activate(nodes) %>% 
  mutate(evc_raw = centrality_eigen(weights = mig_count_2000, directed = TRUE),
         evc_std = centrality_eigen(weights = mig_std_d, directed = TRUE))
mig_evc_df <- as.data.frame(mig_g) %>%
  select(country_name, country_code = name, 
         evc_raw, evc_std)
datatable(mig_evc_df)

Use a Blockmodel to Create a Simplied Representation of the Graph Depicting Connections Based on Raw Flows

Construct a blockmodel using the original migration data. I think that the easiest approach to aggregating the data is to merge the information on block membership to the edgelist data.frame that you created by dropping the dyads with zero flows. From there, you can use group_by and summarize in the usual way and then turn the resulting data.frame into network data using as_tbl_graph.

Since the data are directed, you will need to treat this as a multiplex network (i.e., a network with multiple relations), which means stacking an adjacency matrix on top of its transpose using rbind prior to measuring structural equivalence. If you are measuring equivalence using the dist function, you will need to either transpose the matrices after stacking or use cbind to put the matrices side-by-side instead of stacking them on top of each other.

#measure equivalence
rec_mat <- as.matrix(as_adj(mig_g, attr = "mig_count_2000"))
send_mat <- t(rec_mat)
comb_mat <- cbind(rec_mat, send_mat)
dist_mat <- dist(comb_mat)

#partition nodes
mig_clust <- hclust(dist_mat, method = "ward.D2")
plot(mig_clust)

mig_block_df <- data.frame(name = mig_clust$labels,
                           block = cutree(mig_clust, k = 6))

#merge and collapse data
bm_df <- mig_df %>%
  left_join(mig_block_df, by = c("origin_code" = "name")) %>%
  rename(origin_block = block) %>%
  left_join(mig_block_df, by = c("destination_code" = "name")) %>%
  rename(destination_block = block) %>%
  group_by(origin_block, destination_block) %>%
  summarize(mig_mean = mean(mig_count_2000)) %>%
  filter(mig_mean > mean(mig_mean))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'origin_block'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
#plot simplified graph
bm_g <- as_tbl_graph(bm_df)
ggraph(bm_g, layout = "stress") +
  geom_edge_fan(arrow = arrow(length = unit(2.5, "mm"),
                               type = "closed"),
                end_cap = circle(1.5, "mm")) +
  geom_node_point(color = "red") +
  geom_node_label(aes(label = name), repel = TRUE, label.size = 0) +
  theme_graph()
